Arc–Backarc Exchange Along the Tonga–Lau System: Constraints From Volatile Elements

, , , ,
Journal of Petrology, Volume 63, Issue 8, August 2022, egac072, https://doi.org/10.1093/petrology/egac072
Published:
19 August 2022

Abstract

Analyses of olivine-, pyroxene- and plagioclase-hosted melt (now preserved as glass) inclusions (MI) in submarine glasses and subaerial scoria from seven volcanoes along the volcanic front of the Tonga arc provide the first comprehensive dataset including volatile contents (H2O, CO2, S, Cl and F) for this arc. Maximum water contents at each volcano are typical (3–5 wt %) of other arc volcanoes worldwide, and within each volcano, water generally correlates with sulfur, consistent with degassing but not diffusive re-equilibration. The Tonga arc is notable for the eruption of magmas sourced from strongly depleted upper mantle, including boninites in the northern half of the active arc. A key question has been whether such boninites are derived from high degrees of melting actively occurring under the arc, driven by high mantle temperatures and water contents, or from high integrated degrees of melting including melting of depleted mantle in the backarc. This study supports the latter view, based on sub-arc mantle melt fractions of 17–23%, calculated from primary melt water contents and mantle-melt thermobarometry. Such fractions are not high enough to generate boninites from a typical, fertile mantle source in a single melting stage, and melt fractions do not increase north of 22°S, where the boninitic magmas appear. Instead, the northern Tonga arc boninites reflect high cumulative degrees of melting (>30%, with respect to fertile mantle) and occur along the volcanic front where adjacent backarc spreading is fast, proximal and mature. Slab tracers such as the Ba/La ratio peak at around 20–21°S, in the central part of the Tonga arc. A Ba/La peak also appears at about the same latitude in the Lau backarc basin. This peak is consistent with the coolest slab temperatures beneath the arc and backarc at this latitude, as the slab warms to the north due to an increase in mantle potential temperature, and to the south due to less heat extraction from melting. A new concept developed here is cooling of the mantle wedge by melting, due to the supply of the heat of fusion and melt removal. Such a process can cool the mantle by more than 100 degrees, and thus affect slab heating as well. We find a critical distance of slab influence in the Lau spreading centers; back-arc magmas erupted >70 km from the arc are >210 km above the slab, beyond the point of slab dehydration, and show no enrichment in Ba/La. The coupled dynamics of the Tonga arc-Lau basin are rich in their connections, and demonstrate how melting processes beneath the back-arc and arc can affect slab processes, which in turn can affect the composition of fluids that feed the arc and backarc.

Issue Section:
ORIGINAL MANUSCRIPT

INTRODUCTION

Subduction drives mantle circulation and ultimately melting beneath volcanic arcs. Magmas are produced as volatiles from the subducting plate migrate into the hot core of the convecting mantle wedge, and also as mantle in the backarc drives melting via upwelling (Grove et al., 2002). Nowhere are these two melting processes expressed more clearly than in regions with active spreading behind the volcanic arc. In these coupled systems, the volcanic arc is clearly connected to subduction, generally aligned with a ~100 km depth contour in the slab (Syracuse & Abers, 2006), erupting magmas with several wt % H2O and trace elements derived from recycling of subducted material (Plank, 2005; Plank et al., 2013). The backarc proximal to the arc is organized into spreading centers, some morphologically similar to mid-ocean ridges (Sleeper & Martinez, 2014), where mantle decompression and melting are driven by plate spreading. The interaction between these two melting regions, one driven by plate convergence and one by plate spreading, drives complexities in mantle flow with the potential to create a diversity of magma compositions.

Numerical models show coupled and evolving mantle flow beneath arcs and their associated backarcs (Hall et al., 2012). Initially, the systems may be separated by distinct flow regimes, but as spreading continues, the arc and backarc may begin to share mantle and/or melts even as they migrate apart (Hall et al., 2012). On the other hand, backarc systems that propagate spatially toward the arc may evolve from initially distinct melting regimes to interacting ones (Pearce et al., 1995; Escrig et al., 2009). Two competing processes may drive circulation in opposing directions. Subduction induces mantle circulation that drives trenchward flow from the backarc into the wedge corner beneath the arc. This process sets up a ‘pre-condition’ whereby material that has already melted beneath the backarc may melt again beneath the arc (Ewart & Hawkesworth, 1987; McCulloch & Gamble, 1991; Woodhead et al., 1993; Kincaid & Hall, 2003; Pearce, 2005). Such a process creates a refractory mantle depleted in incompatible elements that may give rise to distinctive high-Si, high-Mg, low-Ti magmas termed boninites (Duncan & Green, 1987; Cooper et al., 2010; Hall et al., 2012; Pearce & Reagan, 2019; Pearce & Arculus, 2021). On the other hand, spreading and decompression in the backarc draws in mantle from a wide region, and potentially the sub-arc mantle, which may itself have already melted and/or may convey water and chemical tracers from the slab. Examples exist of both backarc depletion of arc mantle sources (Ewart & Hawkesworth, 1987; Caulfield et al., 2008; Nebel et al., 2018) and arc depletion of backarc mantle sources (Kamenetsky et al., 1997; Martinez & Taylor, 2002; Nebel et al., 2015). Some studies have emphasized the separation of arc and backarc melting regions (Langmuir et al., 2006), while others have demonstrated a connection (Pearce et al., 1995). In some regions, the backarc seems to inherit structures and fluxes from the sub-arc mantle (Taylor & Martinez, 2003; Escrig et al., 2012; Arai & Dunn, 2014). All of these processes may occur in different parts of evolving arc-backarc systems.

The unique dynamics of coupled arcs and backarcs not only creates complexity, but also provides a wider aperture to view mantle flow, melting and fluid transport in subduction zones. By their very spatial form, arcs sample a limited part of the mantle flow field and slab depths (Syracuse et al., 2010). Backarcs, especially those that have formed at different distances to the slab and arc, potentially sample varying mantle and slab temperatures and compositions (Escrig et al., 2012). The sharing of melting and fluid regimes between the arc and backarc may constrain the rates of mantle flow (Cooper et al., 2010) and fluid migration pathways from the slab (Pearce et al., 1995; Langmuir et al., 2006; Kelley et al., 2010), two processes that are otherwise very difficult to determine.

With these debates and goals in mind, we have carried out a study of the Tonga arc along almost its entire length (Fig. 1). The novel aspect of our study is the new data we provide on the concentrations in melt (now preserved as glass) inclusions of volatile elements (measured as H2O, CO2, S, Cl, F), the first such comprehensive study for the Tonga arc. Water data in particular are essential for quantifying conditions of mantle melting beneath the arc, and so deconvolve backarc and sub-arc processes. A limited portion of the data have been previously published in a study of Volcano A in the Tonga arc, an unusual example of a magma of boninite composition erupting at the volcanic front of an active arc (Cooper et al., 2010; Pearce & Arculus, 2021); in the development of H2O/Ce as a slab surface thermometer (Cooper et al., 2012), and in a survey of arc magma H2O contents and their remarkably limited range of 4 +/− 1 wt % (Plank et al., 2013). Nonetheless, this paper provides the comprehensive melt inclusion (MI), glass, phenocryst and whole rock (WR) data set that we have generated along the Tonga arc (Cooper, 2009). The MI data can also be downloaded in a single table in the global arc compilation in Rasmussen et al. (2022). The current study also focuses on the many submarine volcanoes that characterize Tonga arc volcanism, providing new major and trace element data. Previous work has focused on the Tonga islands (notably Bauer, 1970; Ewart & Hawkesworth, 1987; Regelous et al., 1997; Turner et al., 1997; Caulfield et al., 2008; Beier et al., 2017), which are more sparsely distributed along the arc. The inclusion of the submarine reaches of the arc thus provides a more comprehensive along-arc view with which to compare recent studies along the length of the backarc spreading centers of the Lau Basin (Bézos et al., 2009; Escrig et al., 2009, 2012). Recent geophysical studies also provide new constraints of melting, mantle temperature and flow within the broader Lau Basin (e.g. Arai & Dunn, 2014; Zha et al., 2014; Menke et al., 2015; Wei et al., 2015; Wei et al., 2016; Zha & Webb, 2016; Wei & Wiens, 2018). With these new data, we focus on the following key questions: (1) What are the conditions of mantle melting under the modern Tonga arc? (2) Are the unusually depleted, boninitic magmas found in the Tonga arc generated by extensive melting beneath the modern arc, or in part by prior melting under the backarc basins? (3) Are the slab fluid fluxes sampled in backarc magmas the same as or different from those sampled in the adjacent arc magmas?

Background and geologic setting

The Tonga arc is a predominantly submarine volcanic chain in the southwestern Pacific Ocean, sandwiched between the hot spot-related Samoan islands to the north and the Kermadec arc to the south (Fig. 1). Volcanism results from the westward subduction of the Pacific Plate beneath the Australian Plate and several microplates of the Lau Backarc Basin (Zellmer & Taylor, 2001). Rapid clockwise rotation of the Tonga arc accompanied by extension within the Lau Basin generates many rifts and spreading centers located at various distances behind the arc. The spreading centers proximal to the arc are segmented into two systems, the Southern Lau Rift and the Fonualei Spreading Center in the southern and northern sections of the Lau Basin, respectively (Watanabe et al., 2010; Ruellan et al., 2003; Keller et al., 2008). Other spreading centers are active in the western part of the northern Lau Basin (Northwest Lau Spreading Center; Rochambeau Rifts; not shown on Fig. 1) and the Central Lau Spreading Center. Within each system, the onset age and extent of spreading decreases to the south, due to southward ridge propagation. The shear wave velocity of the upper mantle beneath the Lau Spreading Centers is among the lowest in the planet, likely a combination of hot mantle and melt retention (Wei et al., 2015).

The Tonga–Lau region offers a unique opportunity to study systematic variations in magmatic processes within a single subduction zone that represent extremes in tectonic rates and magma compositions. The combination of rapid extension within the Lau Basin and subduction at the Tonga Trench leads to convergence rates that increase northward to a maximum of 24 cm/yr, the highest in the world (Bevis et al., 1995). The history of the subducting plate beneath the South Pacific Gyre, starved of continental input and nutrients, represents among the slowest sedimentation rates and thinnest subducted sedimentary section globally, comprising ~70 m of pelagic clay and chert (Plank & Langmuir, 1998; d’Hondt et al., 2011; Plank, 2014). The sub-arc slab surface temperatures (SSTs) are estimated to be at a global minimum beneath Tonga, at ~730°C, consistent with a cool slab predicted to result from the fast convergence of the ~100 Ma subducting Pacific plate (Syracuse et al., 2010; Cooper et al., 2012). In addition, Tonga arc magmas possess unusual geochemical compositions, including severe depletions in high field strength elements (Woodhead et al., 1993; Caulfield et al., 2008), globally high Ba/Nb (Turner & Langmuir, 2015) and H2O/Ce (Cooper et al., 2012), large U disequilibrium excesses (Turner et al., 1997) with Pa deficits (Bourdon et al., 1999), low Na6.0 and high Ca6.0 (Plank & Langmuir, 1988), unusually high Si for a given Mg content or Mg#, and the eruption of boninites in young arc volcanoes (Cooper et al., 2010; Pearce & Reagan, 2019).

Cooper et al. (2010) also emphasized the boninitic heritage of magmas erupted in the northern half of the Tonga arc, using a discriminant based on high Si6.0 and low Ti6.0 of erupted melts (SiO2 and TiO2 concentrations at 6 wt % MgO, respectively). Their results showed a transition around 22°S along the Tonga arc, north of which the volcanoes erupt magmas with boninitic heritage. The backarc to the north of 22°S also contains more mature spreading centers, contrasting with the young rift zones and nascent spreading centers to the south. Based on this relationship, Cooper et al. (2010) suggested that boninites in mature arcs form in subduction zones with active backarc spreading centers, where corner flow may deliver refractory mantle (the residuum of mantle melting within the backarc melting regime) into the arc melting regime, and as a consequence, second-stage primary melts (boninites) may be generated beneath the arc (after Duncan & Green, 1987; Ewart & Hawkesworth, 1987; Pearce, 2005; Kincaid & Hall, 2003; Woodhead et al., 1993). A conceptual evolutionary model predicts that varying durations of backarc spreading in the Lau Basin, in addition to other factors such as the geometry of the arc-backarc system and the efficiency of mantle overturn within the wedge, may variably deplete the arc mantle source along the strike of the Tonga arc. Such behavior was also demonstrated with a geodynamic model by Hall et al. (2012), which examined the thermochemical evolution of the sub-arc mantle under the influence of a migrating backarc spreading center. Prior studies have promoted two views on the creation of highly depleted magmas in the Tonga–Lau region. Some emphasize multi-stage melting, remelting and pre-conditioning, as outlined in the Cooper et al. (2010) and Hall et al. (2012) studies highlighted above. Others emphasize extreme degrees of active of melting that create depleted magmas in a single process (Falloon & Danyushevsky, 2000; Escrig et al., 2012). Distinguishing between these two views requires firm constraints on the pressure and temperature of melting and the H2O content of the mantle, as these govern the melt fractions possible during active melting. This is the goal of the current study, developing and then exploiting new data on the H2O concentration in melt inclusions.

In the past decades, research expeditions have discovered numerous submarine volcanoes along the Tonga arc. Indeed, most of the magmatism along the Tonga arc is apparently submarine, even though most previous work has focused on the more accessible islands. In 2003, the SS02/2003 Research Voyage of the Australian Marine National Facility (Tonga–Eastern Lau Vents Expedition (TELVE)), guided by multi-beam swath maps generated by the R/V Sonne SO167 expedition (Stoffers et al., 2003, 2006), carried out dredging of the southern submarine volcanoes of the Tonga arc (Volcanoes 1 to 19); and in 2004, the SS11/2004 Research Voyage (Northern Tonga Vents Expedition (NoToVE)) sampled and surveyed the northern submarine volcanoes (Volcanoes A to O) (Fig. 1). The swath bathymetry revealed volcanic edifices and collapsed caldera complexes, and target locations, such as satellite cones and fresh lava flows, were subsequently dredged (Fig. S1). For this study, we selected ~30 rock samples from 15 submarine volcanoes spanning the length of the Tonga arc (see Supplementary Table S1 for the sample list; full dredge and sample descriptions are provided in Plank & Arculus, 2018, and are registered in SESAR). In addition, we studied seven samples from Tofua and Foa islands, which were collected in 2005 (Caulfield et al., 2008; Caulfield et al., 2011; Caulfield et al., 2012). Tofua is a subaerial volcano located in the central portion of the Tongan volcanic front, and Foa is a subaerial reef located 70 km east of Tofua—the ancient expression of the Tonga arc prior to backarc extension. The sample from Foa is thought to represent a distal fallout deposit from the caldera-forming ignimbrite eruption column at Tofua ~1 ka (Caulfield et al., 2011).

In order to facilitate discussion of the along-strike features of the coupled arc–backarc system throughout this paper, we break up the Tonga–Lau system into four regions (Fig. 1):

  • Southern region, which is defined by the propagating southern end of the Valu Fa and Southern Lau Rifts south of 22.25°S. It includes the Tonga arc from Ata southward;

  • South-central region, which includes the Eastern Lau–Valu Fa spreading centers and is defined by the appearance of boninites in the Tonga arc north of 22.25°S (Cooper et al., 2010) and a major chemical discontinuity in the backarc at 20.5°S (Escrig et al., 2009). This region includes Volcano 5 through Hunga Ha’apai in the Tonga arc;

  • North-central region, which includes the Eastern and Central Lau Spreading Centers, is defined by the region north of 20.5°S to 18°S, where the Fonualei Rift begins. This region includes Volcano B through Late in the Tonga arc;

  • Northern region, which includes the Fonualei Rift and other rifts north of the Mangatolu triple Junction and the active part of the Tonga arc from Volcano L northward.

Note, these regions pertain to the entire Tonga–Lau system and are not the same as the segments Escrig et al. (2009, 2012) define separately for the ELSC and Fonualei systems.

Pre-eruptive H2O contents are difficult to determine due to the strong dependence of volatile solubility on pressure. The decrease in pressure upon ascent promotes degassing, and volcanic rocks that erupt at the surface, or even under water, may contain only a fraction of their initial dissolved H2O, CO2 and S (Newman et al., 2000). To circumvent this problem, melt inclusions—pockets of melt that become sealed at pressure within a phenocryst during crystallization—may be used to recover pre-eruptive, undegassed magmatic volatile contents, which are vital for understanding subduction zone processes (Anderson, 1979; Sobolev & Chaussidon, 1996; Wallace, 2005; Plank et al., 2013). Here, we present H2O measurements for seven volcanoes that have yielded samples containing melt inclusions with high volatile concentrations: from north to south along the arc: Volcanoes L, F, Tofua/Foa, D, A, 7 and 19 (Fig. 1). In total, 29 WR samples, 11 submarine-quenched glasses and over 150 melt inclusions and their phenocryst hosts were analyzed to determine the chemical and volatile composition of Tonga arc melts.

ANALYTICAL METHODS

The focus of this study on MIs required targeting rapidly quenched, glassy submarine lavas and small-diameter tephra, as H2O may diffuse out of melt inclusions through host olivine at magmatic temperatures on the timescale of minutes to hours (Lloyd et al., 2013; Barth et al., 2019). We thus limited our analyses to glassy MIs found within the outer few centimeters of submarine lavas, or within <2 cm scoria lapilli collected on Tofua and Foa, which naturally quenched in contact with cold seawater and ambient air, respectively. We did not attempt to re-homogenize the MIs by reheating, and we only selected MIs that were naturally glassy and free of cracks.

Methods employed here are the same as those reported in Cooper et al. (2010). Detailed information documenting sample preparation and analytical procedures for MIs, WRs, glasses and phenocrysts are included in Supplemental Information (doc file and footnotes to Tables S1–S8). In summary, MIs and glasses were analyzed for major elements by electron microprobe (Table S4), trace elements by laser ablation ICP-MS (Table S5) and volatile elements by SIMS ion microprobe (Table S4). WRs were analyzed for major elements (Table S2) and trace elements by solution ICP-ES and –MS (Table S3). Host phenocrysts were analyzed for major elements by electron microprobe (Table S6) and trace elements by laser-ablation ICPMS (Table S8). Oxygen isotopes were measured in four samples by mass spectrometry following laser fluorination (Table S7). The oxygen fugacities and Fe3+/FeT ratios of the pre-eruptive magmas are calculated using the oxybarometer based on the partitioning of bulk vanadium between olivine phenocrysts and WR or MI compositions (Supplement and Table S9). Photographs of each melt inclusion and host crystal are included in Supplement B.

RESULTS

Whole rock/glass compositions

The major element compositions of submarine Tonga lavas studied here (as well as those in Hekinian et al., 2008; Graham et al., 2008 and Timm et al., 2011) are shown in Fig. 2, compared to those of subaerial volcanic rocks from the literature. The Tonga arc volcanics as a whole span a compositional range from basalt to rhyolite, although most analyzed samples are basaltic andesites. The submarine samples have expanded the number of basalts analyzed and generally extend the range of compositions previously identified in the subaerial arc to both higher MgO compositions (Volcano A and L, >9 wt % MgO) and higher SiO2 compositions (Volcano F and C glasses, 73–75 wt % SiO2). Both submarine and subaerial samples include unusual high-SiO2 basalts and high-MgO basaltic andesites that can be classified as boninites (Le Bas, 2000) or as more evolved magmas of boninite heritage (Cooper et al., 2010; Figs 3 and 4). Submarine lavas encompass the extreme, from true boninites and high Si6.0 glasses at Volcano A in the south-central region to true basalts and low Si6.0 lavas at Volcano 19 in south. Notably, volcanoes that erupt boninitic magmas (Si6.0, >53 wt %) occur only in the northern and central regions of the Tonga arc (Fig. 3).

Trace element variations are also illustrated in Fig. 3, with plots of latitude vs Ti6.0, a measure of incompatible element depletion, and Ba/La ratio, a tracer of slab fluids (Elliott, 2003). Like high Si6.0, low Ti6.0 (<0.65 wt %) characterizes the northern and central parts of the arc, and in fact, these features together are the defining characteristics of a boninite heritage (Cooper et al., 2010 and Fig. 4). Such low Ti6.0 concentrations (Cooper et al., 2010) as well as that of other high field strength elements (e.g. Nb, Ta, Hf, Zr) and key ratios (e.g. Nb/La) are extreme globally in the Tonga arc (Woodhead et al., 1993; Caulfield et al., 2008). Indeed, as far as we are aware, Volcano A submarine lavas have the lowest concentration of Nb (~100 ppb) of any modern volcanic rock on Earth. The new submarine samples illustrate how the extreme Ti6.0 depletion does not extend to south of 22°S, and so is only a feature of the northern and central part of the arc (Fig. 3b). On the other hand, Ba/La peaks (>100) in the south-central region of the arc at Volcano A, drops to <50 to the south at Ata and to the north to Volcano L (Fig. 3c). Prior work has demonstrated that volcanics in the northern region have different Ta/Nd and Pb isotope systematics from the rest of the arc, requiring a distinct mantle or slab source (Turner & Hawkesworth, 1998; Timm et al., 2013; Beier et al., 2017; Storch et al., 2022). Volcano L also has an LREE-enriched REE pattern, unlike the rest of the arc.

Melt inclusions and their crystal hosts

The primary goal of this study was to obtain estimates for the volatile concentrations in Tonga magmatic liquids, and for this we analyzed MIs. At their most straightforward, MIs are trapped aliquots of undegassed magma, retained at the pressure of entrapment inside an inert host crystal. The reality is much more complex, and MIs may exchange with their host crystal or host magma after entrapment, may internally crystallize and/or degas and may originate from a magma that is not cogenetic with the host magma (Danyushevsky et al., 2000; Kent, 2008; Gaetani et al., 2012; Rasmussen et al., 2020; Barth & Plank, 2021). In order to assess such processes, we consider here the phenocryst hosts to the MIs, the relationship between the MIs and the host magmas in terms of both major and trace elements, and finally the MI volatile abundances.

Most of the Tonga MIs studied here are hosted in olivine, with the exception of those from Tofua, which are hosted primarily in clinopyroxene, and those from Volcano F that are hosted primarily in plagioclase. In general (Fig. 5), the highest forsterite hosts (up to Fo92–93) are found in lavas with the highest Mg# (from Volcanoes A and L), and the lowest Fo olivines and pyroxenes (<Mg# 70) are in the lowest Mg# lavas (from Volcanoes F and 19). Some hosts appear to be uniform in Mg#, and in equilibrium with their WR and glass compositions (Volcano F and Tofua TF1062). More commonly, however, MIs are hosted in a range of phenocryst compositions, the upper end of which approaches Mg# equilibrium with the WR (e.g. Volcano A and L, Fig. 5). In Tofua sample TF1170, MIs are hosted in clinopyroxene that have much higher Mg# (85–90) than would be in equilibrium with the WR (Mg# ~75).

Major element characteristics of the MIs are generally similar to those present in the WR and groundmass glass populations (Fig. 6). For example, Volcano A MIs are the highest in MgO while those from Volcano F are among the most evolved. Some MIs, however, possess anomalous compositions. For example, while Volcano A inclusions largely fall along a line of olivine fractionation between the WR and matrix glass in MgO–Al2O3, many have anomalously high CaO concentrations (>12 wt %; Table S4 and Fig. S2). Such high CaO is a relatively common feature of MIs trapped in primitive phases (Schiano et al., 2000) and is typically interpreted to form from clinopyroxene–dissolution reactions (Danyushevsky et al., 2004). The high-Fo olivines from Volcano L also contain some MIs with high CaO, some in excess of 15 wt %, and with widely varying FeO*, some with concentrations greater than and others less than the WR or glass (Fig. S2). Very high FeO* inclusions exist at Volcano 19, up to 15 wt % FeO*, likely caused by plagioclase fractionation. Most of the Tofua MIs plot near their WR or glass hosts, but most also record clinopyroxene fractionation in their declining CaO with declining MgO. Some MIs have very high Al2O3 concentrations (>19 wt % at Volcano D), while others are lower than their WRs (Volcano F and 7), reflecting plagioclase fractionation (Fig. 6). As recognized previously in other MI studies (Danyushevsky et al., 2004; Portnyagin et al., 2019), the Tonga MIs record a range of complex processes in their major elements, not all of which are reflected in the WR or glass compositions.

Figure 7 plots averages of trace element ratios Ba/La and Zr/Y in MIs from each sample vs the WR host and host glass (when available). In general, MIs with anomalous major elements (as described above, >12% CaO or >19% Al2O3) were not selected for laser ablation trace element analyses. If MIs are cogenetic, they should possess the same ratios of incompatible elements as the host rock/glass, and this is largely true for Zr/Y, with the exception of Volcano 19 and the MIs hosted in Tofua mafic phases (clinopyroxene and olivine; the plagioclase-hosted MIs plot with the WR). In the Volcano 19 and Tofua cases, the MIs plot at lower Zr/Y than their magma hosts. On the other hand, with the exception of Volcano A, the Ba/La of MIs is strongly correlated with the host WR Ba/La. Here Volcano 19 and Tofua clinopyroxene-hosted MIs conform with the systematics in the other volcanoes. Despite some offsets, the MIs capture the same large range in Ba/La (40 to >100) as the lavas.

Volatiles

The Tonga arc MIs have a diversity of volatile concentrations, with H2O and S generally co-varying within each volcano (Fig. 8a). Such co-variations are common in other arc MI suites (Wallace & Edmonds, 2011) and are consistent with magmatic degassing during decompression, as volatiles exsolve from melt into the vapor phase (e.g. Fiege et al., 2015). As is observed in arc MI suites worldwide, the maximum H2O concentration measured from each volcano varies from ~2 to 5 wt %, with an average of ~4 wt % (Plank et al., 2013). The highest H2O contents (4–5 wt %) are found at Tofua, Volcano A and L, and the highest S contents are found in Volcano D, L and 7 (Fig. 8). In some cases, the highest H2O contents were measured in clinopyroxene- and plagioclase-hosted MIs, supporting the utility of other MI hosts in addition to olivine. The H2O/Cl ratios of the least degassed inclusions vary widely from 15–60 (not shown), similar to arcs worldwide (Ruscitto et al., 2012), and inconsistent with seawater contamination (Kent et al., 2002). The CO2 concentrations of the measured glass within the inclusions is uniformly low (<350 ppm; Table S4) mostly likely due to exsolution into a vapor bubble that is common in most Tonga melt inclusions (Hartley et al., 2014; Moore et al., 2015). We did not attempt to restore the CO2 concentration within the inclusions (Rasmussen et al., 2020) and do not discuss the CO2 data further.

(A) MI Ba/La is strongly correlated to the host WR Ba/La, but shifted to lower values by about 15% on average. (B) MIs have the same Zr/Y as host lavas, except for Volcano 19, and Tofua MI in high Mg# cpx. Tofua WR is average and stdev of 4 other Tofua samples measured with the same methods as the other WR (see Table S3). If error bars are not visible, they are smaller than the symbol size.

The maximum H2O concentrations recorded in the MIs may yet be lower than the primary magma concentrations, as there is no guarantee that the MI did not trap melt that had already degassed, or did not lose H2O diffusively through the mineral host during ascent (Barth et al., 2019). Nonetheless, there are three arguments against the maximum H2O concentrations representing extensively degassed compositions. The first is that many of the MIs are trapped in very primitive mafic crystals (i.e. Mg# > 88, as for Tofua, Volcano A and L, Fig. 8) and so presumably preserve melt compositions extant early in the magmatic evolution of the specific volcano host. Volcanoes 7 and F contain MIs in very primitive plagioclase (>An90). If extensive H2O loss had occurred, this would have driven extensive crystallization (due to the rise in liquidus and cotectic temperatures), and yet not much crystallization is allowed to maintain Mg# > 88 and An>90 phenocrysts. The plagioclase-hosted MIs have somewhat lower H2O (2.5–3.5 wt %) than the maximum found in primitive olivine- and clinopyroxene-hosted inclusions (4–5 wt %), and this could be due to some degassing before plagioclase saturation, which is expected to occur after olivine and clinopyroxene in H2O-rich melts. The MIs in lower Fo olivines from Volcanoes 19 and D also contain somewhat lower H2O (3.0–3.5 wt %) than those in the more primitive mafic hosts. This could also be due to late entrapment after H2O degassing, but we conclude this is unlikely for Volcano D, which contains MIs with the highest S contents (2500–3000 ppm).

Plotted here are a sub-set of data from each volcano, for the mineral host (indicated in the legend) that includes melts with the highest water contents. (a) For most volcanic suites of melt inclusions, H2O and S co-vary, consistent with coupled degassing during magma ascent. (b) Water concentrations in melt inclusions are plotted against their mineral host composition. Uncertainty in mineral compositions are smaller than symbols.

Indeed, the second argument for the Tonga MIs preserving initial magmatic H2O concentrations is that S is not extensively degassed. The high S concentrations in many of the Tonga MIs (>1000 ppm) suggest that H2O has not yet degassed extensively. The covariation of H2O and S in most of the MI suites moreover argues against major rapid H2O-exchange by diffusion through olivine, as this would destroy such covariation (because S does not partition into nor diffuse rapidly through olivine). For example, if MIs stalled in a shallow magma storage region, they would equilibrate with the exterior degassed magma and have similar, low H2O content at variable S (Rasmussen et al., 2018). This is observed in some Volcano A inclusions (with ~1.5 wt %), but did not affect the entire population, which extends up to 5 wt % H2O. If MIs re-equilibrated at depth with a magma with higher H2O, then they would have constant H2O and variable, but high S. This is not observed (i.e. a vertical trend at high S concentration in Fig. 8a). Some inclusions that have similar S but variable H2O (i.e. horizontal trend in Fig. 8a, such as some MIs from Volcano D and 19) might have experienced diffusive H2O loss during stalling upon ascent.

The third argument against major H2O-loss from the MIs is the agreement with H2O concentrations predicted using the plagioclase–liquid hygrometer of Waters & Lange (2015). Although plagioclase may arrive on the cotectic later than olivine and clinopyroxene in water-rich magmas at high pressure (e.g. Parman et al., 2011), and therefore possibly after the magma has degassed some H2O, the plagioclase- and olivine-hosted MIs in samples from Volcanoes 7 and 19 (where both have been measured) give a comparable range of H2O concentrations. The hygrometer in Waters & Lange (2015) is based on the exchange reaction of anorthite and albite components between plagioclase and melt as a function primarily of temperature and melt water content. Thus, given the composition of a melt inclusion and its plagioclase host, and an independent estimate of temperature, the hygrometer can be used to predict the H2O content of melt. The problem with using this hygrometer, however, is the significant dependence on temperature, which is often not known independently. One could use an independent thermometer, such as the Mg partitioning between olivine and melt, to estimate the magmatic temperature. Given this thermometer is also dependent on the H2O content, we can co-solve for temperature and H2O concentration using both the plagioclase-melt and olivine-melt equilibria. Because plagioclase has a greater sensitivity to H2O, and olivine to temperature, the slopes of the equilibria on a H2O–T diagram are different (Fig. 9 inset), and allow a unique T–H2O to be estimated for every melt inclusion. In practice, we use the WR composition and the average of three published thermometers (see Fig. 9 caption) to determine the olivine-melt H2O–T relationship, and then calculate the T and H2O for each plagioclase-hosted melt inclusion using the intersection with the plagioclase-melt H2O–T relationship. Figure 9 shows that the H2O concentrations measured in the MIs are consistent with those calculated from the olivine–plagioclase-melt equilibria. Despite disequilibrium issues that may affect silicic systems (Humphreys et al., 2016), the consistency shown here suggests equilibrium between olivine, plagioclase and melt in the samples, and useful accuracy of the published thermohygrometers for the mafic Tonga inclusions. Moreover, it also argues against H2O loss from the MIs during ascent, otherwise measured H2O concentrations would be inconsistent with the major element equilibria, which take substantially longer to re-equilibrate than H2O. This test suggests that ascent was rapid enough to prevent H2O loss through the plagioclase or olivine, and that measured H2O concentrations in the MIs are likely those of the storage region.

The example in the inset is for melt inclusion Volc-F-plag25_mia and yields H2O = 2.3 wt % and T = 1063°C. The arguments presented above based on the primitive nature of many of the melt inclusion hosts, the undegassed S contents, and the plagioclase–olivine-melt equilibria, support the integrity of the MIs as recorders of magmatic H2O concentrations. Given that many of the MIs within a given population still reflect some degree of degassing and diffusive loss, in the modeling below, we take the maximum H2O concentration for each population as the best estimate of the parental concentration for that volcano.

Oxygen isotopes

The oxygen isotopic composition of olivine phenocrysts from Volcanoes D and 7 (δ18OVSMOW of 5.01 to 5.04, respectively, Table S7) lie within the range of normal MORB (i.e. δ18OVSMOW of 5.0–5.2, see Eiler et al., 2005) and at the low end of other island arc volcanoes (Eiler et al., 2000). Two different samples from the boninitic Volcano A, however, show higher δ18OVSMOW of 5.2–5.3. While only slightly higher than N-MORB, this could signal a contribution of heavy oxygen from the upper portions of the subducting slab (sediments and low-temperature hydrothermally altered crust). This slight shift in O isotopes in Volcano A is consistent with its higher H2O (4–5 wt %), H2O/Cl (60), and the overall higher expression of slab tracers (i.e. Ba/La, Fig. 3c) with respect to the other Tonga arc volcanoes. Boninites with δ18O enrichments have been observed previously for samples from Vanuatu and New Caledonia (Eiler et al., 2000).

DISCUSSION

Melting conditions beneath the Tonga arc

Several steps are needed to assess the conditions of mantle melting beneath the Tonga arc. The first is the estimation of primary melt compositions (i.e. in equilibrium in the mantle) using erupted compositions. Below we describe the screening process and olivine-addition calculations performed. The second is the estimation of the pressure and temperature of equilibration in the mantle based on the primary melt compositions. For this we utilize the mantle melt thermobarometer of Lee et al. (2009). Third, we combine the P–T–H2O systematics for the primary melts to estimate the degree of melting beneath the arc and the extent of depletion of the mantle prior to arc melting.

Estimation of primary melt compositions

The study of subduction zone processes requires knowledge of the chemical compositions of primary melts—melts in equilibrium with the mantle. Unfortunately, such melts rarely erupt. During transit to the surface, most primary melts experience some extent of crystal fractionation, reaction and/or assimilation. Such processes will overprint primary melt compositions and typically drive them to lower Mg# and, in island arc magmatic systems, to higher SiO2. Within the Tonga arc, near-primary melts have been sampled only at Volcano A (Cooper et al., 2010), where the erupted WR composition in one of the dredges (ND-04) is in equilibrium with Fo90 olivine (Fig. 5), which could exist in the mantle. Nonetheless, the presence of Fo92–93 olivines in this sample (and in Volcano L) point to a more primitive magma than the one that erupts, which minimally would require some olivine addition to restore to initial concentrations. Here, we estimate primary melt compositions for many Tonga arc volcanoes using the most primitive WRs and glasses, and project them to primary compositions by addition of olivine. We did not use the major element concentration of the MIs because they have been variably affected by complex processes happening before and after entrapment (Fig. S2). The MIs are used primarily to estimate the H2O concentration of the parental magma.

To identify the most primitive compositions, we applied a sample screen. Tonga WR and glass compositions from this study and the literature were evaluated for the effects of crystal fractionation and assimilation on the basis of Harker diagrams (as in Figs 6 and S1, and see Table S10 for identification of samples that passed the screen). The most primitive melts lie on or near olivine-only control lines and/or contain only olivine phenocrysts, which are generally the highest Mg# phase in the samples (with the exception of Tofua, where clinopyroxene and olivine with > Mg# 88 both exist; Table S6 and Caulfield et al., 2012). Thus, only erupted melts with major element compositions that reflect largely olivine-only fractionation were considered. We assessed this mostly on the basis of MgO–Al2O3 and MgO–CaO systematics to exclude those samples that appear to reflect fractionation of clinopyroxene (CaO decreasing with MgO) and plagioclase (Al2O3 decreasing with MgO). This is generally true for samples with less than 5 wt % MgO (Fig. 6), and so to facilitate the screen, we only considered erupted melts with MgO >5 wt % (based on anhydrous compositions, normalized to 100%). Some samples with MgO > 5% MgO have also been documented or appear to reflect crystal accumulation or assimilation, and so were excluded. Kao, Tofua and Tafahi include enough high MgO samples that we could be more conservative, and thus for these volcanoes, we only included those with MgO > 6–7 wt %. Eighty-two major element compositions from 18 volcanoes passed the screen (Table S10). The screened erupted melt compositions are in equilibrium with olivine ranging between Fo80 and Fo90. Unfortunately, the screen eliminated all samples from Volcano F.

Next, primary compositions were calculated by adding olivine to the compositions that passed the screen. Equilibrium olivine was calculated at increments of 0.1 wt %, assuming KD(Fe/Mg)ol/liq = 0.3, until the melt was in equilibrium with Fo90–93. This range was based on that typical of mantle olivine (Sobolev & Danyushevsky, 1994; Lee et al., 2009) and based on the maximum Fo observed in phenocryst populations from these volcanoes (Fig. 8b). In detail, we corrected compositions from volcanoes with basaltic heritage to Fo90 (Fig. 4), and those with a boninite heritage to Fo93, reflecting the higher Fo olivine contained within the boninitic lavas (Fo92–93) and consistent with their more refractory (higher Mg#) sources (Cooper et al., 2010). As we demonstrate below, the choice of mantle Fo affects P–T but not melt fraction appreciably. In carrying out these calculations, it is important to take into account the Fe3+/FeT of the melt, which as described above, is based on the fO2 calculated from the partitioning of V between olivine and melt (and Table S9). Only Fe2+ enters into the olivine equilibrium calculations, while Fe3+ is passively diluted by the addition of olivine. In this way, the fO2 is not buffered, but Fe3+/FeT starts with that estimated for the erupted composition (21–27% for the different volcanoes), and decreases during olivine addition. This approach is consistent with measurements of Fe3+/FeT ratios in mid-ocean ridge basalts, which show that Fe oxidation state varies during basalt crystallization as a system closed to oxygen exchange with its surroundings (Cottrell & Kelley, 2011). The average amount of olivine added was around 20% to reach Fo90, and 40% to reach Fo93. Prior to the olivine addition correction, the least-degassed H2O contents measured in melt inclusions (i.e. the maximum H2O) were incorporated into the erupted major element compositions. For volcanoes with no measured H2O or fO2 estimates, we used the average of the other volcanoes (3.54 wt % H2O and 24% Fe3+/FeT).

Pressures and temperatures of melt equilibration in the mantle

The pressure and temperature conditions of primary melt generation for volcanoes in the Tonga arc were estimated by applying the mantle melt thermobarometer from Lee et al. (2009) to the primary melt compositions. The thermodynamic basis for the thermobarometer is the well-known temperature dependence of Mg partitioning between olivine and liquid (e.g. Roeder & Emslie, 1970) and the strong pressure dependence of Si activity in melt co-existing with olivine and orthopyroxene (Carmichael et al., 1970). Lee et al. (2009) use the large experimental database of major element compositions available through LEPR (Hirschmann et al., 2008) to calibrate the Si-activity barometer in particular, including for hydrous compositions. The model co-solves the thermometer and barometer, and enables estimation of both with no prior assumptions as to P or T. This is accomplished by incorporating a Si-term into the Mg-thermometer to account for the pressure effect, and then using that temperature as input to the Si-barometer. Although the model includes the effect of H2O on melting temperatures, it underpredicts the basalt liquidus depression according to more targeted experiments and compilations (Medard & Grove, 2008; Tenner et al., 2012; see also the discussion in Plank & Forsyth, 2016). Thus, we calculate the temperatures dry with the Lee et al. (2009) model, and then apply the H2O-depression off-line, using the function developed in Tenner et al. (2012) (the 1 GPa curve in their Fig. 7b; which is very similar to that of Medard & Grove, 2008; expression provided in the footnote to Table S10).

Uncertainties on the thermobarometer calibration are on the order of ±30–40°C and ±200 MPa (Lee et al., 2009). Other uncertainties are in the estimation of H2O, Fe3+/FeT and Fo. Increasing Fe3+/FeT by 10%, lowering Fo by 1.2 units, and raising H2O by 1.5 wt % each have an equivalent effect to lowering temperature by 50°C. Because we have measurements of H2O and estimates of Fe3+ for the Tonga lavas, the major uncertainty is in the assumption of mantle Fo. Variations in Fo, however, affect both P and T in such a way to largely parallel the mantle solidus, and so have a small effect on the estimation of melt fraction (see below and Fig. 10b). While this method provides a single pressure and temperature for primary melt generation, it is more plausible that melt generation is polybaric and therefore occurs over a wide range of conditions. We assume the pressures and temperatures estimated here represent the average or final melting conditions.

Primary pressures calculated for Tonga arc magmas (Table 1, Fig. 10a) are consistently lower than 2 GPa, with some approaching that expected for the local Moho (~25 km, following Crawford et al., 2003, equivalent to ~0.7 GPa assuming a crustal density of 2700–2800 kg/m3). Primary temperatures range from ~1225 to 1325°C for Fo90 and from ~1335 to 1450°C for Fo93. The Fo90 melts lie along the dry solidus, which is a coincidence, as they contain high H2O contents (~3 wt %) and so must instead be following a finite melting isopleth (see below).

Degree of melting beneath the arc

The melt fraction (F) of the mantle can be calculated uniquely from T, P and the H2O concentration in the liquid. We follow Langmuir et al. (2006), Kelley et al. (2010) and Hirschmann (2010) in using a cryoscopic approach to calculate F. Three quantities go into this calculation: (1) the dry solidus, (2) the cryoscopic effect (freezing point depression) on melting isopleths due to H2O melt concentration and (3) melt productivity as a function of temperature (i.e. dT/dF). Important with respect to the origin of Tonga arc boninites, we also consider fertile and depleted lherzolite mantle sources. For the solidus, we use the expression in Hirschmann (2000) for fertile lherzolite, and we raise that solidus T by 39°C for depleted lherzolite (after Wasylenki et al., 2003). For the cryoscopic effect due to H2O, we again use the function illustrated in Tenner et al. (2012) appropriate to 1 GPa (given in Table S10). For the melt productivity of fertile lherzolite, dT/dF = 550-40P (i.e. 5.5°C per % melting at 1 atm), where P is in GPa, based on the pressure-function in Hirschmann (2010) (his Fig. 1) and similar to that in the experiments of Baker & Stolper (1994) (Fig. S3). At 22% melting, which marks the crucial point of clinopyroxene exhaustion in Baker & Stolper’s (1994) experiments, dT/dF increases to 1200-40P, based on the harzburgite melting interval in Wasylenki et al. (2003) (see Fig. S3). This reflects the significant increase in temperature required to achieve the same melt fraction once clinopyroxene is consumed. For depleted lherzolite melt productivity, we are again guided by the experiments of Wasylenki et al. (2003), where melting is productive while clinopyroxene is in the melting mode (dT/dF = 373-40P), but after clinopyroxene is consumed at 9% melting, dT/dF once again increases to 1200-40P (Fig. S3). For those volcanoes that plot in the boninite field in Fig. 4, we used the depleted lherzolite melting model to calculate F. For those volcanoes that plot in the basaltic field in Fig. 4, we used the fertile lherzolite model (although below we show that similar melt fractions are obtained if the basaltic magmas are also corrected to Fo93 olivine and equilibrated with depleted lherzolite).

Figure 10b illustrates graphically how the calculation works for 3.5 wt % H2O and F of 10%, using the relationships specified above. A melt fraction of 10% requires a temperature increase above the solidus of ~50 degrees (calculated from the melt productivity term), while the cryoscopic effect of 3.5 wt % H2O (the average of Tongan magmas) lowers melting isopleths by ~100°C. Thus the 10% melting contour with 3.5 wt % H2O lies at a temperature~50°C below the dry solidus and below all Tonga magmas. If the source is instead a depleted lherzolite, then both the solidus and melt productivity change to increase the temperature of the 10% melting contour (for 3.5 wt % H2O) by about 30°C, which is still too low for the Tonga magmas. Thus, a general conclusion from this treatment is that Tonga magmas record higher F than 10%.

Using the H2O content of each melt, and a fertile or depleted mantle source as appropriate, the melt fraction can be calculated for each primary melt. The results indicate 17–20% melting for the northern and central arc (of boninite heritage and equilibrated with Fo93, Fig. 11a), and 20–24% melting for the southern arc (of basaltic heritage and equilibrated with Fo90 olivine). If we treated the basaltic heritage melts the same as the boninitic ones(equilibrated with Fo93 olivine and depleted mantle) the results would have been even more similar (17–19% melting, Table S10, 11). Again, this is because variations in Fo largely parallel melting isopleths. Thus, the degree of melting does not vary strongly along the arc, despite large differences in major and trace element compositions. This is due to the similar H2O contents of the Tonga arc melts and the similar distance (in P–T space) from the appropriate fertile vs depleted solidus for basaltic and boninitic melts, respectively. We could also consider coupling the Fo92–93 boninitic compositions with a fertile lherzolite; in this case F would rise from 18.5% on average to 25%. This is still not appreciably larger than F in the south, despite the fact that this pairing of conditions is inconsistent with peridotite systematics (e.g. laboratory experiments require >30% melting of fertile peridotite to generate Fo92, see Fig. S8 in Plank & Forsyth, 2016). We do not see evidence for anomalously high melt fractions (30–40%) occurring beneath the arc, as predicted by trace element models (e.g. Escrig et al., 2012). This is because melt productivity diminishes dramatically when clinopyroxene is exhausted from the mode. This is clear in anhydrous experiments (e.g. Wasylenki et al., 2003; Fig. S3), and H2O apparently has little effect on harzburgite melting productivity (dT/dF). For example, Parman & Grove (2004) see no change in the melting mode of their harzburgite melting experiments, with and without H2O (0–6 wt %). Likewise, Tenner et al. (2012) find little change in melt productivity from 1.5 to 5% H2O. Thus, it remains difficult to achieve F > 25% without higher H2O or higher T than recorded in Tonga magmas. For example, the H2O content of Volcano A would have to be raised from 4 wt % to more than 8 wt % in order to melt fertile mantle >30%, again due to the dramatic drop in melt productivity once clinopyroxene is consumed at ~22%. Although there is always a concern about H2O loss before and after melt inclusion entrapment, we find for the reasons outlined above (Volatiles Section) that it is unlikely that Volcano A melt inclusions (in ~Fo88 olivines) could lose half their H2O and not reflect great amounts of crystallization (e.g. inclusion LC-A-4, ol28-mia contains 4.74 wt % H2O and is in equilibrium with Fo89 olivine with no post-entrapment crystallization). We conclude that the degree of melting in the mantle beneath the Tonga arc is high (15–25%), but not remarkably so, despite the fact that extraordinarily depleted magma compositions erupt. This points to source depletion as the cause of the magma depletion.

Depletion in the source and prior melting

Although major elements and H2O can constrain the last melting event that generated Tonga arc magmas (Farc), prior melting episodes can also be constrained by considering the concentration of incompatible trace elements. As others have done (e.g. Stolper & Newman, 1994; Langmuir et al., 2006; Portnyagin et al., 2007; Kelley et al., 2010; Escrig et al., 2012), we use TiO2 as a proxy for total melt fraction. This is primarily because Ti is a high field strength element that is expected to be a minor constituent within slab-derived fluid, and the abundance thereof should predominantly reflect mantle melting processes (McCulloch & Gamble, 1991; Klimm et al., 2008). We calculate the total amount of melting from an initial, common fertile mantle composition (Ftotal) from the batch melting equation:
Ftotal=[(TiO2)fert/(TiO2)prim−arc−DTi]/[1−DTi].
(1)
where TiO2fert is 0.133 wt % (from Salters & Stracke, 2004) and DTi is 0.04 (as in Kelley et al., 2006). A fractional melting model in which the melts are aggregated would produce similar results, within 1–2% melt fraction (Kelley et al., 2006). In the southern part of the arc, Ftotal is around 20% (Fig. 11a), in good agreement with the major element melting model for Farc. This supports the notion that fertile mantle supplies the southern arc, and that there is little prior melting or depletion of the arc source. In contrast, Ftotal is in excess of 30–40% in the northern and central parts of the arc, reflecting the very low TiO2 contents that must derive from prior melt depletion of those sources. Given that Farc for the northern and central volcanoes is on the order of 15–20%, there may have been as much as 10–20% prior melting, logically in the backarc prior to remelting in the arc source. The extent of prior depletion is not that simple to calculate, however, because more depleted domains could mix with fertile domains (see below). Nonetheless, the contrast between Farc and Ftotal supports the notion that the Tonga arc boninites found in the northern and central parts of the arc are derived from re-melting of mantle derived from the backarc (Cooper et al., 2010; Hall et al., 2012).
We can calculate the total amount of prior depletion by first calculating the TiO2 in the arc source, again through the batch melting equation:
(TiO2)o=(TiO2)prim−arc [Farc (1−DTi)+DTi]
(2)
where (TiO2)prim-arc, the average concentration of TiO2 in the primary melt, is derived from the TiO2 concentration of the erupted magma (following the olivine addition described above); Farc is as calculated above from T, P, H2O; and DTi is now 0.02 to reflect less clinopyroxene in the mode (and the partition coefficients in McDade et al., 2003). The TiO2 in the arc source, (TiO2)o, is then compared to the fertile concentration (0.133 wt % TiO2), and the extent of depletion is calculated as the amount of melting required to generate (TiO2)o as the residue of first-stage melting, again from the batch melting equation:
Depletion=[DTi/(1−DTi)][(TiO2)fert/(TiO2)o−1]
(3)

So, for example, the TiO2 concentration in the source of Tafahi volcano is calculated to be 0.057 wt % (from a primary melt with 0.27 wt % TiO2 and F = 19%; Table S11). In order to generate a depleted source with 0.057 wt % TiO2 from a fertile one with 0.133 wt % TiO2, a 5.6% batch melt would have to be removed. But there are many other ways to achieve this depletion. It could derive from removing 5.6% batch melt in the backarc in one stage, or it could derive from mixing 43% fertile mantle with 57% mantle that approaches zero TiO2 (at the limit of maximally depleted). Small degrees of fractional melting can efficiently deplete the solid residue of incompatible elements. Most likely, the arc source is a mixture of fertile and variably depleted sources, where the depletion parameter reflects the average depletion in a relative sense (Hall et al., 2012).

The extent of depletion in the southern arc is near zero (Fig. 11b), as would be expected because (TiO2)o beneath the arc is near the fertile value (0.133). This is consistent with Farc ~ Ftotal (Fig. 11a), and so little evidence for either prior melting or prior depletion of the southern Tonga arc mantle. The northern and central Tonga volcanoes reflect greater extents of depletion (3–9%), which derive from the low values of (TiO2)o there (with the exception of Volcano D). This is a direct reflection of the low TiO2 concentrations (<0.65 wt %) measured in the boninitic magmas (Fig. 3b).

Water concentrations in the source

Finally, the H2O concentration in the arc source can be calculated from the melt inclusion measurements (taking the maximum H2O for each volcano, and adding olivine to derive H2Oprim-arc) in a way analogous to (TiO2)o:
(H2O)o=(H2O)prim−arc [Farc (1−DH2O)+DH2O]
(4)
where Farc is as given in Table 1 (and S11), and DH2O is 0.012 (as in Kelley et al., 2006). The H2O concentrations in the source are relatively uniform along the arc (5000–7000 ppm H2O) with the southern arc reflecting slightly higher values than the north and central (with the exception of Volcano A, which has high (H2O)o because of the somewhat higher H2O measured there, >4 wt %; Fig. 11c). Such concentrations are consistent with the trenchward increase in (H2O)o found by Kelley et al. (2006) in the Lau Basin spreading ridges (their Fig. 14), predicting arc source values of >4000 ppm. The Tonga arc (H2O)o concentrations are also similar to the average calculated for the Mariana arc, 3000–9000 ppm (Kelley et al., 2010) and typical for arcs worldwide, 2000–11 000 ppm (Plank et al., 2013).

Summary of melting results and comparison to prior work

Separating the effects of source depletion from the degree of melting is one of the challenges of mantle geochemistry. Here we have attempted to estimate such parameters independently, using melting energetics on the one hand and trace element depletion on the other. In theory, the T–P-H2O of a primary melt is consistent with only one melt fraction F, and we have used experimental parameterizations to calculate this following a cryoscopic approach. The results suggest that the degree of melting is between 17% and 25% for the entire Tonga arc. The calculated F in the southern part of the arc is shifted to slightly higher values (20–24%) than the northern and central parts (17–20%), which is opposite to the sense of depletion in trace elements (e.g. Ti6.0, Fig. 3b) and in major elements (i.e. the lack of boninite heritage in the south; Fig. 3a). Thus, there is no evidence in these calculations that Tonga boninitic magmas are derived by substantially higher degrees of melting beneath the arc than the basalts to the south. This results from the similarity of all Tonga arc magmas in H2O and ∆Tdps (the difference in equilibration T from the dry peridotite solidus at any P; Fig. 10). Likewise, there is no evidence for higher H2O contents in the source of the boninites. (H2O)o is similar along-strike of the arc (5000–7000 ppm), if anything, higher in the south. Instead, the shift in the extent of depletion as recorded in incompatible trace elements (such as TiO2, Fig. 11b) reflects a greater inherent depletion in the arc source in the north. On the other hand, Farc calculated for the southern arc melts from P–T-H2O is similar to Ftotal calculated from TiO2. The consistency between Farc and Ftotal reflects melting of a fertile source in one stage under the arc. The difference between Farc and Ftotal in the north and central volcanoes (Fig. 11a), where Ftotal >> Farc, requires melting of a more depleted source, one that already had Ti extracted by prior melting episodes, logically in the backarc. The arc source for north and central volcanoes is also presumably more refractory (i.e. lacking clinopyroxene in the mode). Boninites require final equilibration with cpx-free peridotite, and this would not occur with Farc of 15–17% if the source were fertile peridotite (i.e. fertile lherzolite must melt > ~ 22% to exhaust cpx; Baker & Stolper, 1994). But if the mantle were depleted by melting in the backarc, clinopyroxene could be exhausted during arc melting with as little as 10% melting of a depleted lherzolite (as in the experiments of Wasylenki et al., 2003; which started with ~10% cpx in the mode and are similar to the residues of 12–13% batch melting of fertile peridotite), satisfying the condition of equilibrium with a cpx-free peridotite for the boninitic melts.

Previous work has also called for prior depletion of the mantle wedge beneath the Tonga arc. For example, Ewart & Hawkesworth (1987) were the first to point out the difficulty of generating the extremely depleted REE and HFSE abundance of Tongan lavas by high degrees of melting, and still satisfy major element constraints. They preferred a model whereby MORB ‘restite’ (i.e. the residue of ~10% melting) from the backarc was remelted under the arc, driven by induced corner flow. Falloon & Crawford (1991) also argued for a depleted lherzolite source for boninites in the northern termination of the Tonga arc. Bourdon et al. (1999) discovered unusual 231Pa deficits relative to 235U in Tonga lavas relative to most arcs, which generally show 231Pa/235U excesses. They explained this occurrence with melting of low modal clinopyroxene in the unmelted arc mantle source and prior melting of the mantle up to 10%. Caulfield et al. (2008) use Nb/Ta ratios to argue for small degrees of prior melting (<1 wt %) in the Tonga arc source. Such small depletions would not remove enough melt or clinopyroxene to create boninites, given the extents of melting (Farc) calculated here (>17%). We have been unable to reproduce the wide range in Nb/Ta in Caulfield et al.’s (2008) samples (Supplement Table S3 provides our re-analysis of some of Caulfield et al.’s (2008) Tofua samples). Nonetheless, the extremely depleted Nb and Ta concentrations provide support (analogous to TiO2) for a melt-depleted source beneath the Tonga arc. Turner & Langmuir (2015) show how the Tonga arc is a global end-member in magmaphile elemental depletion (e.g. Na6.0), and prefer a model whereby crustal thickness relates to the degree of melting in the mantle wedge. The thin oceanic crust of the Tonga arc likely contributes to the overall high degrees of melting that occur there (~20%), but crustal thickness variations are not great enough to explain the factor of 2 depletion in Na6.0 that occurs in the north Tonga arc, which is more likely a product of prior melt depletion in the backarc. Beier et al. (2017) calculate similar degrees of melting (20–30%) and prior depletion (6%) to the values reported here for the northern volcanoes, Tafahi and Niuatoputapu.

Escrig et al. (2012) argue that boninitic magmas in the Fonualei Rift and Spreading Center (FRSC; Fig. 1) are derived from high degrees of melting. Their conclusions are based in part on correlated variations between Ti8.0 (which they take as a proxy of the degree of melting) and Ce/Pb (which they take as a proxy of slab fluids), arguing for a coupling between F and H2O. They develop a quantitative model for melting based on trace elements that predicts 25–40% melting beneath the central Fonualei rift to create the boninite magmas there. Trace element models, however, can be highly non-unique and sensitive to small degrees of fractional melting (as discussed above). Moreover, it is difficult to calculate the extent of melting because no H2O data exist for FRSC melts that are not demonstrably affected by degassing (published measurements are on seafloor glasses, not melt inclusions, Escrig et al., 2012; Keller et al., 2008). Nonetheless, if we assume the same H2O contents as the average Tonga arc (3.54 wt % H2O), then screen, add olivine (Fo90), and calculate P, T, F in the same way as for the arc samples (as in Fig. 10), we calculate F = 18–20% for the FRSC boninites. This is not extensive enough melting to exhaust clinopyroxene and create boninites; nor does it agree with the (one-stage) melting model in Escrig et al. (2012), which resulted in 34–39% melting for the boninites. Increasing H2O has little effect on this calculation, since the effect on F is counteracted by the effect on T (i.e. high H2O drives higher melting but also leads to a greater cryoscopic effect on the calculated temperature, which will lower melting). The only way to increase F appreciably in the FRSC boninites is to equilibrate them with Fo93 olivine and assume lherzolitic initial mantle; in this way F increases to 26–27%. This is still less than the amounts calculated by Escrig et al. (2012) based on Ti depletion, and we note that the highest Fo olivines reported for Fonualei boninites are Fo89 (Keller et al., 2008). It is possible higher Fo olivines exist in the Fonualei boninites, but we find it more likely that an already melt-depleted (refractory) source contributed to the generation of these boninites. Indeed, Escrig et al. (2012) favor a combination of factors, including a refractory source to explain the boninites in the FRSC.

Slab inputs to the Tonga arc and Lau Backarc

Quantifying slab inputs along the arc and backarc

In this section we explore the along-strike variations in inputs from the subducting slab, as highlighted earlier using the Ba/La ratio in Tonga arc lavas (Fig. 3c). Given the close connection between the backarc and arc in the above melting model, we consider here variations in the slab inputs along-strike in the backarc as well. As a starting point, we consider Escrig et al. (2009)‘s proposition that there are spatial relationships shared between Tonga arc and Lau Basin backarc basalts in a host of geochemical parameters, including Ba/La. In a diagram of Nb/La vs Ba/La (Fig. 12a), Escrig et al. showed how backarc regions project from a common MORB mantle composition toward arc compositions and the inferred slab input for that region of the arc. For example, they found that the southern Lau basin basalts project to a Ba/La ratio very similar to that in the southern Tonga arc, and that the projected Ba/La ratio for the backarc basalts increases northward along with the arc ratio. They concluded, along with several previous workers (Kamenetsky et al., 1997; Peate et al., 2001; Kent et al., 2002), that the backarc basalts are mixtures of arc-like melts with melts from the ambient mantle unaffected by subduction, and that the along-strike variations in the backarc are related to along-strike variations in the arc. Questions remain, however, as to whether there are shifts in the latitudinal variations between the arc and backarc that reflect vectors of mantle flow, and if the subduction input to the backarc is the same as that to the arc or different.

Here we build on the work of Escrig et al. (2009), using our more extensive suite of arc geochemical data. We also consider the high Ba/La component in the backarc and arc basalts separately, and examine in finer detail the variations as a function of latitude. The first step is to assess the Nb/La of the mantle beneath the arc prior to subduction input. Given the different melting histories outlined above and the potential for enriched mantle domains in both the backarc and arc, it seems unlikely that every sample in the arc and backarc share a common initial mantle Nb/La and Ba/La. It is also clear that some basalts in the Lau Basin, particularly those from 20.5–21°S (the geochemically anomalous ‘Central group’ of the ELSC in Escrig et al., 2009), do not derive from the same source mantle as the basalts to the south (Fig. 12a).

Thus, we independently determine a Nb/La mantle composition for each arc and backarc sample based on Sm/La-Nb/La systematics (Fig. 12b). The premise of this diagram is that the MORB array (from depleted to enriched) forms a trend with a negative slope, while MORB-slab mixing should form a trend with a positive slope. The intersection of these two arrays provides an estimate of the MORB-mantle composition prior to slab input. In practice, each sample is projected onto the MORB array from a nominal slab component with zero Nb/La (i.e. assuming zero Nb from the slab) and a Sm/La ratio equal to the Tonga bulk sediment (0.26; Plank, 2014). We could have also chosen the Sm/La ratio in the 700°C sediment fluid in Johnson & Plank (1999), which is nearly identical (0.27). A 700°C MORB fluid will also have a low Sm/La ratio (0.11 calculated for the Hole 801C altered ocean crust composition of Kelley et al., 2003, using the partition coefficients in Kessel et al., 2005). The exact choice of the Sm/La for projection does not change the topology nor results appreciably (a lower Sm/La will lead to lower Nb/La mantle sources and higher Ba/La fluids for both the arc and backarc). The mantle Nb/La ratio for each sample is then used to determine the Ba/La ratio in the inferred slab fluid by projecting from the mantle value through the sample to the vertical axis on Fig. 12a (again, at zero Nb/La). Table S12 provides the initial and projected trace element ratios for the backarc and arc samples, data sources, and equations used for the linear projections. Figure 12a provides some example projections and comparison to the constant mantle assumption of Escrig et al. (2009).

Figure 13 shows the results of the unmixing calculations, with both arc and backarc compositions plotted against latitude. The Nb/La ratio of the mantle source for the arc is in almost all cases lower than that of the backarc. Both the arc and backarc show increasing amount of enriched mantle (higher Nb/La, enriched isotopes) toward the northern terminus of the arc and backarc. This has been noted previously by many authors (e.g. Danyushevsky et al., 1995; Turner et al., 1997; Lytle et al., 2012; Price et al., 2016; Beier et al., 2017; Storch et al., 2022) and ascribed to incursion of Samoan enriched mantle around the slab edge, subduction of enriched seamounts and/or storage of enriched components in the lithosphere. Most of the backarc has a mantle Nb/La ratio of ~0.5–0.6, consistent with that inferred by Escrig et al. (2009). The greater Nb/La depletion of the arc is consistent with the greater cumulative melting inferred above (Fig. 13c).
