Along-strike variations in Tonga arc (symbols as in Fig. 2) and back-arc (grey triangles) slab and mantle inputs (as calculated from Fig. 12). Orange line passes through the average for each arc volcano to guide eye. Green line is the same for the back-arc. Back-arc spreading centers are labeled in (b): FR (Fonualei Rift), CLSC (Central Lau Spreading Center), ELSC (Eastern Lau Spreading Center), VF (Valu Fa). % of Ba/La from slab is the ratio of the measured Ba/La to that of the slab input, as in Fig. 12a (samples with Ba/La < 15 are plotted at zero). Uncertainties derive from unknown variation in the Sm/La of the slab fluid and width of the mantle array in Fig. 12b.

The Ba/La ratio of the inferred slab input varies dramatically along strike in both the arc and backarc, from zero slab input in the Central Lau Spreading Center (18–20°S, with measured Ba/La < 10, like MORB) to Ba/La > 200 at 20.8°S (Volcano A). The remarkable observation is that the Ba/La of the slab input peaks in both the arc and backarc at the same latitude (20.5–21°S). The backarc peak is sharper (0.5° latitude width) than the arc peak (extending north ~1.5° latitude). There are some sporadically higher Ba/La values in the northern arc (a single sample from Tafahi) and in the south (Volcano 18), and an anomalously low value at Volcano B (behind the volcanic front), but the peak in the center of the arc is the dominant regional signal (in other slab proxies as well, such as B isotopes, Leeman et al., 2017).

The coincidence of the arc and backarc Ba/La slab input peaks at 20.8°S supports an E–W connection, either with E–W flow between the arc and backarc melting regions (possibly through ridge suction) or E–W delivery of slab fluids/melts to the arc-backarc. Plate convergence flow lines are very close to E–W, ~N80E (Escrig et al., 2009). The E–W connection seems at odds with the ~NS flow of asthenosphere inferred from seismic anisotropy (Menke et al., 2015). Either this along-strike flow is too slow to deflect the vertical rise of slab fluids or ridge suction of arc melts, or the anisotropy derived from olivine fabrics is not simply related to mantle flow. The narrower peak in the backarc could relate to the different sampling of sources by different ridge segments, although the boundaries of the peak do not coincide with segment boundaries (e.g. the geochemical boundaries are in the middle of segment ELSC-3 to the middle of segment ELSC-4; Escrig et al., 2009).

It is difficult to test whether the enrichments in the backarc derive from arc melts directly or from similar slab input as the arc—both mixing processes are co-linear in Fig. 12a if the mantle sources are similar. However, there are some arc-backarc pairs where it may be possible to distinguish between these two scenarios. One involves the samples at 20.8°S that define the Ba/La peak, because the arc and backarc samples have appreciably different mantle source compositions. The arc samples (Volcano A) mix from a very depleted mantle (Nb/La = 0.3–0.36) to very enriched slab input (Ba/La = 170–220, see red line in Fig. 12a). The backarc sample (KLM0417-R113, Gale et al., 2013) that mixes to similarly high Ba/La (183, see gray line in Fig. 12a) derives from a much less depleted mantle source (Nb/La = 0.58) and so defines a mixing line that does not pass through the arc samples. This suggests that the backarc is not simply entraining arc melts. This view is also supported by regions where the arc and backarc slab input appears to be quite distinct in Ba/La, for example at 20 and 22°S (Fig. 13a). On the other hand, it is clear that the FRSC has captured the arc melting regime (the arc volcanoes there are inactive). There is likely an evolution in time and space, such that the arc and backarc tap separate melting regions when >25 km apart (Lin et al., 2010). After that distance, the primary flow-field leads to advection of backarc material under the arc and not arc melts under the backarc (Lin et al., 2010). Thus, while it is difficult to test for direct arc-melt capture given the sparse sampling of the arc, the existing data support the process whereby most of the backarc does not simply entrain arc melts, but is fed by separate mantle sources and slab inputs than those that feed the arc. Logically, the backarc slab inputs would derive from greater depths in the slab than arc inputs (e.g. slab depth is ~210 km beneath the ELSC backarc at 20.5°S vs 125 km beneath Hunga volcano in the Tonga arc; Wei et al., 2017). Slab-melange diapirs seem an unlikely delivery mechanism of slab material to the arc or back-arc given the very thin sediment layer on the Pacific plate (<100 m), below the threshold predicted for buoyant instabilities (Behn et al., 2011).

The magnitude of the slab input can be quantified graphically from Fig. 12a as the distance along the mantle-slab mixing line (% of slab Ba/La). That is, most of the backarc compositions plot closer to the MORB end-member, while most of the arc compositions plot closer to the slab end-member (Fig 12a). On the other hand, some of the backarc samples in the south extend further toward the slab input end-member. For these, slab input is 60–80% of the Ba/La signal, like the arc. When this quantity is plotted as a function of latitude (Fig. 13b), it is apparent that the proportion of slab input increases dramatically southward along the ELSC to the Valu Fa Ridge (from 21–23°S). The entire FRSC (18–16°S) overlaps in its slab input with the arc, and indeed, has apparently captured the arc melting region (here the previous arc volcanic front is currently inactive; Keller et al., 2008; Escrig et al., 2012). On the other hand, all the CLSC basalts have Ba/La < 10, wholly within the MORB range, with no evidence for slab input (Jenner et al., 2012). These systematics suggest a relationship between % slab Ba/La and distance to the arc, where distant backarc spreading centers (CLSC and northern ELSC) receive no slab input, and proximal backarc spreading centers (Valu Fa, southern ELSC and FRSC) receive slab inputs that approach those of the arc. Indeed, a plot of % slab Ba/La vs the arc-orthogonal distance between the backarc and arc shows clear relationships and thresholds (Fig. 14). Samples that are greater than 70 km from the arc show no clear slab input (all samples have Ba/La < 15). This suggests a threshold to slab input at a distance within ~70 km of the arc. This threshold largely appears within the ELSC, at a latitude of ~20.6°S, where the first samples with Ba/La > 15 appear (impressively, this boundary was noted by Pearce et al. in 1995, on the basis of six dredge samples). Sleeper & Martinez (2014) and Sleeper et al. (2016) also noted a transition in back-arc morphology at ~70 km from the arc for both the ELSC and FSC that they interpreted to result from a transition in the extent of hydration of the mantle. Thus, there is excellent correspondence between geochemical and seafloor expressions of slab input to the backarc. As the backarc approaches to within 30–40 km of the arc (Valu Fa and FSC), the % slab input increases to values approaching those of the arc (see also Jenner et al., 1987; Escrig et al., 2012).

Fig. 14
Open in new tabDownload slide

Distance from the back-arc sample to the arc front vs % of Ba/La from the slab (as in Fig 13b). Distance between back-arc and arc is along a line orthogonal to the arc volcanic front (as in Escrig et al., 2012). At a distance >70 km from the arc, there is no slab Ba/La (for this plot, samples are required to have Ba/La > 15 to plot above zero). As the back-arc approaches within ~70 km of the arc, it begins to receive slab Ba/La. Within 40–50 km of the arc, the back-arc receives a comparable slab input as the arc (shown as orange rectangle). Depth to the slab from seismic cross-section at ~20°S from Wei et al. (2017).

What controls the threshold to slab input in the backarc at ~70 km from the arc? Plotted in Fig. 14 are also the corresponding depths to the slab from the recent study of Tonga slab seismicity of Wei et al. (2017). The threshold distance to the arc, which again appears within the ELSC at about 20.5°S, is where the depth to the slab is ~210 km, or 7 GPa. According to the P–T calculations in Wei et al. (2017), this pressure is where the final, major dehydration reaction occurs within the slab, serpentine breakdown below the slab Moho. It is likely that no clear slab input appears at greater distances in the backarc because the slab is no longer supplying significant fluid and solute.

Along-strike control and arc-Backarc exchange

In this section, we consider the question of why there is a peak in the Ba/La ratio of the slab input in the middle of the Tonga arc and at approximately the same latitude in the backarc. In considering this question, we will bring together different observations regarding the slab and mantle processes along-strike in the Tonga–Lau systems. We explore the proposition in Ruscitto et al. (2012) that the Ba/La ratio in the slab input reflects slab temperature, especially in a place like the Tonga arc where the intrinsic Ba/La ratio in the subducting sediments is not particularly high (i.e. unlike Central America, where sediments subduct with a bulk Ba/La ratio of 183 vs 14 for Tonga sediments; Plank, 2014). In support of this proposition is the along-strike variation in H2O/Ce, which also peaks at Volcano A (Fig. 15e; note there are no H2O measurements in melt inclusions from the ELSC, and so it is not possible to compare the arc and backarc H2O/Ce). The H2O/Ce ratio of fluids and melts has been linked closely to slab temperature, due to its very strong control on the solubility of REE and H2O concentration of fluids (Plank et al., 2009). Although there will be other effects due to solid phase chemistry (e.g. monazite and allanite, Skora & Blundy, 2012; Stepanov et al., 2012) and fluid chemistry (F, Cl, Tropper et al., 2011), temperature has an effect of several orders of magnitude on the H2O/Ce ratio, especially at temperatures near the slab surface (H2O saturated) solidus, as is the case for the Tonga slab (Cooper et al., 2012). For example, at sub-arc depths (2.5–4.5 GPa), the H2O/Ce ratio in a near-solidus melt at 730°C is ~7000, while only 30 degrees lower, at 700°C, the sub-solidus fluid has H2O/Ce of ~100 000 (Plank et al., 2009). The magnitude of the H2O/Ce ratio measured in the Tonga arc melt inclusions is within this range, from 3400 at Volcano 7 to >20 000 at Volcano A, the highest of any modern arc composition (Cooper et al., 2012). These high H2O/Ce ratios for Tonga arc magmas are consistent with the Tonga slab having the highest thermal parameter globally, up to 20 000 km (Syracuse & Abers, 2006), and thus the coolest thermal structure (i.e. the thermal parameter is the product of the convergence rate, the plate age, and the sine of the dip angle, Kirby et al., 1996, and relates inversely to SSTs from thermal models; Syracuse et al., 2010). Thus the peak in Ba/La and H2O/Ce in the slab input logically relates to lower SSTs in the central region of the arc.

The problem with this logic is that predictions from the slab thermal parameter alone place the coolest SSTs in the northern end of the Tonga arc (where convergence rates are the fastest in the world, Bevis et al., 1995, and the plate age is greatest, Müller et al., 2008), where Ba/La ratios are not the highest. While one sample from Tafahi volcano in north Tonga has very high calculated Ba/La in the slab fluid (with no H2O measurements available to calculate H2O/Ce), the rest of the samples from Tafahi and Volcano L have lower Ba/La than Tofua, Hunga and Volcano A in the middle of the arc (Fig. 13a). This is even while taking into account the enriched mantle that supplies the northern arc (i.e. higher Nb/La mantle, Fig. 13c). There is also evidence, however, that this more enriched mantle is also hotter than the mantle that supplies the rest of the Tonga arc. This evidence includes 1480°C temperature estimates for the primary magmas that give rise to the north Tonga boninites (Falloon & Danyushevsky, 2000, see Fig. 10). Using the same method employed in this study, we also calculate melting temperatures ~100°C hotter for the north Tonga boninites than the rest of the Tonga arc (NT in Fig. 10). This hotter mantle could result from the proximity of the Samoan plume to the northern end of the Tonga slab (Danyushevsky et al., 1995; Druken et al., 2014). There is no evidence, however, for elevated 3He/4He in the arc-proximal spreading centers and hence Samoan Plume ingress at present (Lupton et al., 2015). Wei et al. (2016) also show a northward decrease in shear-wave velocities (SV) at 100 km depth beneath the back-arc basins (from 4.4–4.5 km/s to 4.3–4.4 km/s), consistent with a regional increase in mantle Tp northward. At depths shallower than 100 km, SV is dramatically lower (<4.0 km/s) likely due to the presence of melt (Wei et al., 2015), and so we take SV at 100 km being more representative of the regional Tp. The heating of the slab as it descends is driven by the advective, poloidal flow of hot mantle to the wedge core (England et al., 2004). Especially important is the temperature of mantle at 80–125 km depth, because shallower than this depth, there may not be enough slab coupling to drive mantle flow to warm the slab (Wada & Wang, 2009; Syracuse et al., 2010), and much deeper than this is beyond sub-arc depths. Thus, the critical region that determines sub-arc slab T is 80–125 km depth, deeper than the arc melting regime (Fig. 10) but relevant to the backarc mantle. Given the potential temperature estimate for the southern Tonga–Lau region of 1475°C (calculated for basalts in the Valu Fa rift; Wei et al., 2015), we estimate Tp of 1580°C in the north (following the argument above for 100°C warmer temperatures in the north). SST scales to mantle Tp (England & Katz, 2010), and so this northward increase in Tp of the mantle counteracts to some degree the northward increase in thermal parameter of the slab. While a northward increase in Tp explains why the northern Tongan slab is not the coolest, it does not explain why the center of the arc is. For this we take into account another important effect on mantle temperature, and that is the effect of melting (heat of fusion) and melt removal on mantle T.

The critical region of the mantle for slab heating (~125–80 km) is also where melting in the backarc has lowered the temperature of the mantle in order to supply the heat of fusion (Hf, Fig. 10a). For example, Wei et al. (2015) estimated a wet-decompression melting path for Valu Fa backarc basalts that initiates >150 km (Tp = 1475°C), and by 80 km depth the mantle has melted 15–20% and has cooled 115°C relative to the potential temperature adiabat (1500°C at 2.5 GPa; Fig. 10a). This cooling is entirely due to Hf. Thus, it is not only the regional Tp adiabat (which we assume is sampled by the backarc) that determines the temperature of the mantle that warms the slab at 80–125 km depth, but also the extent of melting this mantle has undergone. In the central part of the Tonga arc, the mantle underwent 15–20% melting in the backarc (Fig. 15g), and so should be cooler than the Tp of 1475°C used to model slab PT paths in Wei et al. (2017). The net effect will be the coolest temperatures in the middle of the arc. In the north, higher initial Tp will balance the cooling due to Hf. In the south, the extensive melting under the backarc has yet to reach the arc or slab (basalts there do not reflect prior melt depletion, Fig. 11).

An example calculation illustrates these three competing effects on SSTs: mantle Tp, thermal parameter, and Hf (Fig. 15). For convenience, we start with the slab temperature model calculated in Wei et al. (2017) at 3.5 GPa (~under the arc) and for constant Tp (1475°C) and modify it to include regional variations in Tp and Hf. The calculations in Wei et al. (2017) illustrate well the effect of thermal parameter alone, with the faster, older slab in the north leading to cooler (730°C at 18°S) SSTs (dashed line in Fig. 15d) than in the south (775°C at 23°S). When we include an increase in Tp to the north, counterbalanced with the cooling effect of Hf, the SST remains at 730°C. This is roughly at the slab solidus and predicts H2O/Ce ~ 7000, as observed. In the south, the Tp remains at 1475°C, and there is no Hf effect, so the SST remains at 775°C. This predicts H2O/Ce of ~4200, similar to that observed. In the central part of the region (~21°S, near the slab Ba/La peak), the Wei et al. (2017) SST is 745°S. We estimate a mantle Tp here of 1500°C (dashed line in Fig 15c), giving a mantle temperature of 1525°C at 80 km depth. Prior melting, however, has reduced T, we assume conservatively by 85°C (as opposed to the 115°C highlighted above). This provides a new mantle T at 80 km of 1440°C (solid line in Fig. 15c). This is 60°C cooler than the 1475°C Tp mantle used in the Wei calculation, and so we adjust the SST by 30°C (using the scaling in England & Wilkins, 2004, which also holds for more realistic olivine rheology, Peter van Keken, pers. comm.), yielding 715°C (solid line in Fig. 15d). This is below the H2O-saturated slab solidus (~730°C) and would yield fluids with very high H2O/Ce, like the 20 000 observed at Volcano A. Thus in the center of the arc, the Hf effect (driven by substantial melting in the backarc and full advection of this mantle under the arc) wins out over the small increase in Tp predicted. The small drop in SST calculated is enough to shift H2O/Ce substantially, because of the dramatic drop in the solubility of Ce in subsolidus fluids. In this way, the along-strike changes in the backarc mantle Tp and melting history affect the thermal structure in the slab, which in turn affect the composition of slab fluids and so H2O/Ce and Ba/La along the arc. Figure 15 panels show the along-strike changes in these parameters, where mantle and slab temperatures are affected by Hf (green shading) and where the slab surface is predicted to be subsolidus beneath the arc (blue shading).

The question now becomes how to explain the Ba/La peak in the backarc. One would expect slab fluids that supply the backarc to reflect greater pressures and temperatures, and therefore different compositions. However, Tonga slab PT paths are very steep (e.g. nearly isothermal, Wei et al., 2017) and the SST could remain below the solidus for the central Tonga–Lau region, thus delivering a similar high Ba/La fluid to the arc and backarc.

Relationship to other slab tracers and comparison to prior work

Although we focused on a specific suite of slab tracers here—Ba, REE, Nb, H2O—the systematics we have quantified are general, and relate to other geochemical systematics of Tonga–Lau magmas. For example, Leeman et al. (2017) shows B/Nb and δ 11B also peaking around 20°S, and favors aqueous-fluid dominated transport from the slab superimposed on a highly depleted mantle. Turner et al. (1997) emphasized the globally high U/Th and Ba/Th values that occur in the central Tonga arc, and also implicated a slab-fluid component. Escrig et al. (2009) showed how the Ba/La systematics between the arc and backarc are also developed for Ba/Th, Pb isotopes, and Ce/Pb.

One notable point of comparison involves the source H2O contents from the previous section (H2Oo) and trace element proxies of slab fluids. It is often assumed that trace element ratios such as Ba/La (or Ce/Pb, Escrig et al., 2012) can be used as a proxy for the amount of H2O in the source of arc magmas. This is not validated in the current data set. While Ba/La peaks in the middle of the Tonga arc (Fig 3c) and varies by >400%, H2Oo varies only slightly, decreasing northward by about 30%. We have argued that this reflects SSTs, where small variations near the solidus may lead to large variations in Ba/La (and H2O/Ce). The water content of the arc source will depend on not only the composition of the slab fluid/melt but also the quantity of this fluid with respect to the mantle. This in turn will depend on the fluid migration pathway (Wilson et al., 2014), the slab fluid supply rate and the mantle wedge turn-over rate. If the mantle wedge were stagnant, we might expect higher water supply in North Tonga, where convergence rates are highest, and might be expected to deliver a higher flux of water. Because both the fluid supply rate and the mantle wedge overturn rate are linked through the convergence rate, however, the H2O concentration per parcel of mantle could remain relatively constant. Indeed, despite having the highest convergence rates globally, the H2O content of the Tonga arc mantle source (5000–6500 ppm) is average for arcs worldwide (Plank et al., 2013). One of the frustrations in the study of arc volatiles is that while many trace element and isotopic ratios are effective tracers of slab fluids and melts, they are not necessarily effective proxies for water concentration in the source of arc magmas (Plank et al., 2013).

Synthesis of slab, arc and Backarc interactions in the Tonga–Lau system

The arc, backarc and slab along the Tonga–Lau system are rich in their interconnections. A summary of how different boundary conditions drive systematic along-strike variations in the chemical composition of arc and backarc volcanics is presented in Fig. 16. The driving boundary conditions involve an old slab that increases in convergence rate to the north, attaining the highest plate rates on the planet; a hot mantle wedge, with potential temperature (and seismic velocities) that are among the highest (and lowest) on the planet; and an extensive set of backarc basin spreading centers some of which (in the north) remove melt and heat from the mantle to an extent and rate that exceeds most other spreading centers globally, while others (in the south) are propagating and only just starting to remove melt. These extreme boundary conditions lead to extreme geochemical characteristics of Tonga arc volcanism: boninitic magmas highly depleted in elements that are removed during mantle melting (e.g. Ti, Nb) and highly enriched in elements preferentially transported in low-temperature slab fluids (e.g. Ba and H2O) relative to those that are not so readily mobilized (e.g. REE). These features are developed to varying degrees and to an extreme extent in certain regions of the Tonga arc.

Fig. 16
Open in new tabDownload slide

Arc-back-arc provinces (color shading) in the Tonga–Lau system, summarized from systematics in Figs 11, 13 and 15. See text for description of the along-strike variations in slab, arc and back-arc (BA) relationships.

Here we summarize the along-strike changes in the Tonga–Lau system (Fig. 16), beginning with the southern region. This region is defined by southward propagation of nascent backarc ridges such as the Valu Fa that approach within 30–40 km of the arc. The propagating tip of the Southern Lau Rift is currently at 23°40′ (Ruellan et al., 2003). The southernmost volcanoes in the Tonga arc studied here (Volcano 19, Monowai and Volcano V) thus do not yet have backarc spreading behind them. Despite the close proximity to the arc of the Valu Fa, there is no evidence that the backarc spreading in this part of the southern region has been going on long enough to deplete the sub-arc mantle (Stages I, II and III in Cooper et al., 2010). The basalts in this region do not reflect degrees of mantle melting greater than 25%, Farc = Ftotal, the sub-arc mantle is fertile, and there are no boninites. While the arc is not influenced by the backarc in this region, the backarc receives a strong slab input signal, with >50% of the Ba/La derived from the slab (Fig. 14), and may even share the arc melting region at its closest approach to the arc and slab at Valu Fa.

In the south-central region of the Tonga–Lau system, more mature backarc spreading creates extensively melt-depleted mantle that is drawn by slab-driven corner flow under the arc, where it melts again. This creates boninitic magmas with aggregated Ftotal of 30–40%. Melt removal in the backarc may have cooled the mantle by ~50°C, in order to supply the heat of fusion, and this in turn may have led to less efficient slab heating, with slab temperatures in this region below the solidus, creating arc basalts with the highest Ba/La and H2O/Ce ratios. Notably, the backarc basalts in this region (the ELSC) also reflect the high Ba/La fluids generated by the anomalously cool slab. In this way, there is a feedback between the slab and backarc: the backarc melting region cools the mantle, which is less efficient at heating the slab, which returns a cool slab fluid to the backarc.

The north central arc has similar attributes to the south central arc due to the mature Central Lau Spreading Center having generated depleted mantle that is now melting beneath the arc, producing boninitic magmas. The backarc basalts, however, differ from those to the south because they form too far from the trench to receive slab input. The depth to the slab is >210 km, apparently too great to generate fluids rich in Ba/La (Fig. 14). Thus, in this region the backarc affects the arc, but the backarc is not affected by the slab.

In the northern region, plate convergence, spreading rates and mantle potential temperature are at their maxima. The close arc approach at the Fonualei Rift and Spreading Center has apparently captured arc magmatism (Keller et al., 2008); the arc volcanoes between 18 and 16.5°S are dormant but have a topographic expression along the FRSC (Sleeper et al., 2016). This unfortunate circumstance did not befall the arc in south Tonga, perhaps due to the slower spreading of propagating Valu Fa ridge. The high mantle temperatures in the north, possibly related to the proximity of hot Samoan mantle (cf. Lupton et al., 2015), lead to extensive melting under the backarc basins (Keller et al., 2008; Escrig et al., 2012), high temperature boninites (Falloon & Danyushevsky, 2000) and extensive depletion under the arc, with Ftotal of >40%. The higher mantle temperature wins over the inefficient conductive heating of the rapidly converging slab to create slab temperatures that are once again above the H2O-saturated sediment solidus. Thus moderate Ba/La ratios are shared by the arc and backarc. In this region, there is also a reverberation of processes, whereby the hot backarc influences slab temperatures, which in turn influence the composition of the slab fluids that feed the backarc.

CONCLUSIONS

This study provides the first comprehensive dataset for the volatile contents of Tonga arc volcanics, and as such, is able to separate the roles of temperature vs water on the origin of Tonga arc magmas, and the extent to which trace elements may serve as proxies for subducting slab-derived water. The focus on submarine volcanism also provides a more detailed along-strike perspective than has been possible in the past, allowing for direct comparison of arc and backarc processes. The primary results include:

  • 1.

    Tonga arc melt inclusions from seven volcanoes distributed over 10 degrees of latitude record maximum H2O contents of 2.5 wt % H2O (Volcano F) to 4.5 wt % (Volcano A). The melt inclusions have incompatible element ratios similar to those in the WRs, and so are representative of the host magma. Despite being associated with the fastest plate convergence rates on Earth, the Tonga arc magmas have H2O contents typical of other arcs worldwide.

  • 2.

    The degree of melting beneath the Tonga arc is relatively uniform, at 17–24%, based on calculated primary melt compositions, water contents and mantle-melt thermobarometry. The total degree of mantle melting, calculated from the Ti contents of Tonga arc magmas, however, varies strongly along strike, from 17–25% in the south (the same as Farc) to >30% in the north, coincident with the occurrence of boninites. These extreme degrees of melting are not occurring due to extreme conditions under the arc, but due to the integrated effects of melting beneath both the backarc and arc. The boninitic arc parents that source Tonga arc volcanism north of 22°S are a reflection of faster, closer and longer duration of backarc spreading in the north Lau Basin, which has produced residual mantle that is now melting again under the arc.

  • 3.

    The Ba/La ratio, a classic tracer of slab fluids and melts, peaks in the middle of the Tonga arc (20–21°S) despite smooth gradients in slab age, convergence rate and wedge melting. The same peak appears at approximately the same latitude in the back arc (ELSC). This feature is consistent with the expected coolest slab temperatures in the middle of the arc, as slab temperatures increase northward due to higher mantle potential temperature, and southward due to less heat extraction from prior melting. The backarc shows no slab influence when >70 km from the arc front, as slab depths are >210 km and beyond the depth of dehydration reactions.

  • 4.

    The Tonga arc–Lau system offers a dynamic view of how spreading and convergence, in close proximity, affect one another. Backarc spreading removes melt from the mantle, and the subducting slab drives trenchward flow of this mantle to melt again under the arc, leading to highly depleted magmas: the unusual arc boninites of Tonga. Backarc melting also removes heat, the heat of fusion, and this can lead to cooler slab temperatures in an already cold slab, and distinctively high Ba/La at the same latitude in both the arc and the backarc. Understanding arc and backarc processes requires integrated study of both in systems where they interact.
